<!-- Hero -->
<div class="hero" id="overview">
  <span class="topic-tag">PHASE 1 · TOPIC 4 OF 8 · EST. 2–3 HOURS</span>
  <h1>Package <span>Managers</span></h1>
  <div class="hero-meta">
    <div class="meta-chip"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--acc)"></div>2–3 hours study</div>
    <div class="meta-chip"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--acc2)"></div>Beginner → Senior</div>
    <div class="meta-chip"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--acc6)"></div>Ubuntu 22.04 LTS</div>
    <div class="meta-chip"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--acc5)"></div>Prereq: T1 + T2 + T3</div>
  </div>
  <p class="hero-desc">Package managers are how Linux systems install, update, and remove software reliably. A broken package manager can take down a production server just as surely as a disk failure. Understanding what happens under the hood — repositories, dependency resolution, dpkg vs apt — separates engineers who blindly run commands from those who can recover when things go wrong.</p>
  <div class="outcomes-grid">
    <div class="outcome-item">Understand the relationship between apt, dpkg, and repositories</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Install, update, remove, and search for packages confidently</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Add third-party repositories and GPG keys correctly</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Hold packages at specific versions to prevent unwanted upgrades</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Understand the full apt package lifecycle</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Work with dpkg directly for forensics and repair</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Understand snap and when to use it vs apt</div>
    <div class="outcome-item">Debug broken packages, unmet dependencies, and locked dpkg</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S1 -->
<div class="section" id="s1">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🧠</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Beginner Intuition</div><div class="section-num">Section 01 — Simple Mental Model</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="note note-mental">
    <div class="note-label">🧠 Mental Model</div>
    <p>Think of a package manager like a <strong>smart app store for your terminal</strong>. Instead of downloading an installer from a website, you tell the package manager what you want by name. It finds the right version, checks that all its dependencies are available, downloads everything, verifies the integrity, and installs it — in the correct order. It also remembers everything it installed so it can cleanly uninstall or upgrade later.</p>
  </div>
  <p>There are <strong>two layers</strong> to understand on Debian/Ubuntu systems, and this layering trips up beginners constantly:</p>

  <div class="pkg-flow">
    <div class="pf-step">
      <div class="pf-icon">🌐</div>
      <div class="pf-title">Repository</div>
      <div class="pf-sub">Remote server with .deb files + metadata</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pf-step active-step">
      <div class="pf-icon">📦</div>
      <div class="pf-title">apt</div>
      <div class="pf-sub">High-level: resolves deps, fetches, calls dpkg</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pf-step">
      <div class="pf-icon">🔧</div>
      <div class="pf-title">dpkg</div>
      <div class="pf-sub">Low-level: unpacks .deb, runs scripts, tracks state</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pf-step">
      <div class="pf-icon">💾</div>
      <div class="pf-title">Disk</div>
      <div class="pf-sub">Files installed to /usr, /etc, /var/lib</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p><strong>apt</strong> is the high-level tool you use daily. It talks to repositories, resolves dependency chains, and calls <strong>dpkg</strong> to do the actual installation. <strong>dpkg</strong> is the low-level tool that unpacks <code>.deb</code> files and maintains the installed package database. You interact with dpkg directly mainly for forensics and repair.</p>

  <div class="note note-try">
    <div class="note-label">✅ Try It Now</div>
    <p>Run <code>apt show curl</code>. Read the output — notice the Version, Depends, and Description fields. This is the package metadata apt reads from the repository.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S2 -->
<div class="section" id="s2">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">📖</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Core Fundamentals</div><div class="section-num">Section 02 — Repositories, packages, and the Debian ecosystem</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3>What is a package?</h3>
  <p>A <strong>.deb package</strong> is a compressed archive containing: the software's files (binaries, libraries, configs, docs), metadata (name, version, dependencies, maintainer), and lifecycle scripts (pre/post install/remove). Every package has a <strong>control file</strong> that declares its name, version, and what other packages it depends on.</p>

  <h3>Package states</h3>
  <p>Every installed package has a tracked state in dpkg's database. Understanding this is critical for debugging:</p>
  <div style="background:var(--surface2);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;padding:14px 18px;margin:12px 0">
    <div class="state-row"><span class="state-badge sb-installed">installed</span><span class="state-arrow">→</span><span class="state-desc">fully installed and configured</span></div>
    <div class="state-row"><span class="state-badge sb-candidate">half-installed</span><span class="state-arrow">→</span><span class="state-desc">install started but failed midway — needs repair</span></div>
    <div class="state-row"><span class="state-badge sb-held">held</span><span class="state-arrow">→</span><span class="state-desc">intentionally pinned — upgrades blocked</span></div>
    <div class="state-row"><span class="state-badge sb-config">config-files</span><span class="state-arrow">→</span><span class="state-desc">removed but config files remain on disk</span></div>
    <div class="state-row"><span class="state-badge sb-purged">purged</span><span class="state-arrow">→</span><span class="state-desc">removed including all config files</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3>Repositories and sources</h3>
  <p>apt fetches packages from <strong>repositories</strong> — servers that host <code>.deb</code> files and signed index files. Ubuntu ships with several default repositories:</p>

