<!-- S5 -->
<div class="section" id="s5">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔬</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Under the Hood</div><div class="section-num">Section 05 — How apt resolves dependencies and installs packages</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note note-hood">
    <div class="note-label">🔬 Under the Hood</div>
    <p>When you run <code>apt install nginx</code>, many steps happen before a single file lands on disk. Understanding this sequence explains every error message you'll encounter.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>What apt install actually does</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># apt install nginx — internal sequence:</span>

<span class="cm"># 1. READ the local package index (/var/lib/apt/lists/)</span>
<span class="cm">#    Find nginx's entry: name, version, dependencies, download URL</span>

<span class="cm"># 2. DEPENDENCY RESOLUTION (the hard part)</span>
<span class="cm">#    Build a dependency graph: nginx needs libpcre3, zlib1g, openssl...</span>
<span class="cm">#    Each dep may need its own deps (transitive closure)</span>
<span class="cm">#    Find versions that satisfy ALL constraints simultaneously</span>
<span class="cm">#    If impossible → "unmet dependencies" error</span>

<span class="cm"># 3. DOWNLOAD .deb files to /var/cache/apt/archives/</span>
<span class="cm">#    Verify checksums (SHA256) against signed package index</span>
<span class="cm">#    If checksum mismatch → abort (prevents tampering)</span>

<span class="cm"># 4. UNPACK via dpkg</span>
<span class="cm">#    Extract .deb archive</span>
<span class="cm">#    Run preinst script (if any)</span>
<span class="cm">#    Copy files to filesystem</span>
<span class="cm">#    Run postinst script (creates users, starts services, etc.)</span>

<span class="cm"># 5. UPDATE dpkg database (/var/lib/dpkg/status)</span>
<span class="cm">#    Mark package as installed</span>
<span class="cm">#    Record all installed file paths in /var/lib/dpkg/info/nginx.list</span></code></pre>

  <h3>GPG signatures and trust chain</h3>
  <p>Every repository's package index is signed by the maintainer's GPG key. apt verifies this signature before trusting the index. Without GPG verification, an attacker could serve malicious packages from a mirror. This is why <code>apt-key add</code> (adding to the global keyring) is deprecated — it trusted ALL repos with that key. The modern <code>signed-by=</code> approach scopes each key to its specific repository.</p>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Check what keys apt trusts:</span>
<span class="cn">apt-key list</span>                      <span class="cm"># deprecated keyring (legacy)</span>
<span class="cn">ls -la</span> /etc/apt/keyrings/          <span class="cm"># modern per-repo keys</span>
<span class="cn">gpg --show-keys</span> /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg  <span class="cm"># inspect a key</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Snap internals: squashfs and confinement</h3>
  <p>Snaps are distributed as read-only <strong>squashfs</strong> images, mounted at <code>/snap/package/version/</code>. They bundle their own dependencies — no system library conflicts. They run in <strong>AppArmor confinement</strong> with declared interface permissions (network, home, camera). Updates are atomic: the new version is downloaded and mounted before the old one is removed, so rollback is always possible.</p>

  <pre><code><span class="cn">ls /snap</span>                           <span class="cm"># see all mounted snap packages</span>
<span class="cn">df -h</span> | <span class="cn">grep snap</span>                 <span class="cm"># each snap mount takes a small /dev/loopX</span>
<span class="cm"># Common complaint: many snaps = many loop devices cluttering df -h</span>
<span class="cm"># Filter: df -h --exclude-type=squashfs</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S6 -->
<div class="section" id="s6">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🏭</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Real-World Usage</div><div class="section-num">Section 06 — Patterns used in production and automation</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note note-real">
    <div class="note-label">🏭 Real-World Patterns</div>
    <p>These are patterns used in Ansible playbooks, Docker images, CI pipelines, and server provisioning scripts.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Non-interactive apt for scripts and Docker</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Set DEBIAN_FRONTEND to prevent prompts in scripts/containers</span>
<span class="kw">DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive</span> <span class="cn">apt install</span> <span class="fl">-y</span> tzdata

<span class="cm"># Docker best practice — combine update + install + clean in one layer:</span>
<span class="kw">RUN</span> apt-get update \
    && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
        nginx \
        curl \
    && apt-get clean \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
<span class="cm"># Why one RUN? Docker caches each layer. Separate update+install layers</span>
<span class="cm"># cause the "cached stale index" problem — install runs against old metadata</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Unattended security updates</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Install unattended-upgrades for automatic security patching</span>
<span class="cn">apt install</span> unattended-upgrades
<span class="cn">dpkg-reconfigure</span> unattended-upgrades   <span class="cm"># enable via interactive prompt</span>

<span class="cm"># Config: /etc/apt/apt.conf.d/50unattended-upgrades</span>
<span class="cm"># Review what it would do:</span>
<span class="cn">unattended-upgrade</span> <span class="fl">--dry-run -v</span>

<span class="cm"># Check when it last ran:</span>
<span class="cn">cat</span> /var/log/unattended-upgrades/unattended-upgrades.log</code></pre>

  <h3>Auditing package history</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># What was installed/upgraded recently?</span>
<span class="cn">cat</span> /var/log/apt/history.log

<span class="cm"># Find when a specific package was installed:</span>
<span class="cn">grep</span> <span class="st">"install nginx"</span> /var/log/dpkg.log

<span class="cm"># List all manually-installed packages (not pulled in as deps):</span>
<span class="cn">apt-mark showmanual</span>

<span class="cm"># List explicitly installed packages (great for provisioning scripts):</span>
<span class="cn">apt list</span> <span class="fl">--installed</span> 2>/dev/null | <span class="cn">awk -F'/' '{print $1}'</span></code></pre>

  <h3>Holding kernel version during maintenance</h3>
  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Never let the kernel auto-upgrade on a production server without planning</span>
<span class="cn">uname -r</span>                           <span class="cm"># current kernel version</span>
<span class="cn">apt-mark hold</span> linux-image-$(uname -r) linux-headers-$(uname -r)
<span class="cn">apt-mark showhold</span>                   <span class="cm"># verify kernel is held</span>
<span class="cm"># When ready for kernel upgrade: apt-mark unhold, then apt full-upgrade, then reboot</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S7 -->
<div class="section" id="s7">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔄</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Modern vs Legacy Tools</div><div class="section-num">Section 07</div></div>
  </div>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Legacy</th><th>Modern</th><th>Key difference</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>apt-get</code></td><td><code>apt</code></td><td>apt has progress bars, better output, auto-cleans. Use apt interactively; apt-get in scripts (stable, predictable output)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>apt-cache search</code></td><td><code>apt search</code></td><td>Same functionality, apt is more readable</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>apt-key add</code></td><td><code>signed-by= in sources</code></td><td>apt-key is deprecated (Ubuntu 22.04+). Global keyring is insecure.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>apt-get dist-upgrade</code></td><td><code>apt full-upgrade</code></td><td>Same behaviour, renamed for clarity</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>aptitude</code></td><td><code>apt</code></td><td>aptitude has a TUI and different resolver. Still useful for complex dep conflicts.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>PPA via <code>add-apt-repository</code></td><td>Manual <code>sources.list.d/</code> + keyring</td><td>More control, more portable, required in containers</td></tr>
  </table>

  <div class="note note-senior">
    <div class="note-label">💡 Senior Engineer Insight</div>
    <p>In shell scripts and CI pipelines, prefer <code>apt-get</code> over <code>apt</code>. The <code>apt</code> command emits ANSI colour codes and progress bars designed for humans — these can corrupt CI logs and cause parsing failures. <code>apt-get</code> has stable, parseable output and has been the scripting-safe choice for decades. Use <code>apt-get -y -qq</code> for quiet, non-interactive scripting.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S8 -->
<div class="section" id="s8">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">⚠️</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Common Beginner Mistakes</div><div class="section-num">Section 08</div></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Running <code>apt install</code> without <code>apt update</code> first:</strong> The local package index is stale. You install an outdated version or get "package not found" for packages that exist. Always <code>apt update</code> before installing.</li>
    <li><strong>Confusing <code>apt remove</code> and <code>apt purge</code>:</strong> <code>remove</code> leaves config files behind. If you reinstall later, old configs take effect and cause confusing behaviour. Use <code>purge</code> when you want a clean slate.</li>
    <li><strong>Forgetting <code>apt autoremove</code>:</strong> After removing a package, its dependencies remain installed as orphans. Over time this wastes significant disk space. Run <code>apt autoremove</code> regularly.</li>
    <li><strong>Installing from random PPAs:</strong> PPAs (Personal Package Archives) can contain anything. They run scripts as root during install. A malicious or abandoned PPA is a serious security risk. Verify the PPA owner and package before adding it.</li>
    <li><strong>Not pinning versions in production:</strong> Running <code>apt upgrade</code> on a production server without testing the new versions first causes unexpected breakage. Pin critical packages and upgrade deliberately.</li>
    <li><strong>Adding the same repo twice:</strong> Causes "duplicate source" warnings and can confuse apt's priority system. Check <code>/etc/apt/sources.list.d/</code> before adding a new repo.</li>
    <li><strong>Killing apt mid-run:</strong> Interrupting an install (Ctrl+C) can leave dpkg in a <code>half-installed</code> state. Never kill apt. If it happens, recover with <code>dpkg --configure -a</code>.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- S9 -->
<div class="section" id="s9">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🏗️</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Common Production Mistakes</div><div class="section-num">Section 09</div></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Running <code>apt upgrade</code> on a live production server unplanned:</strong> A kernel upgrade requires a reboot. A library upgrade (openssl, glibc) can break running services. Always run upgrades in a maintenance window, after testing on staging.</li>
    <li><strong>Not using <code>--no-install-recommends</code> in containers:</strong> Recommended packages bloat Docker images. A minimal nginx container that should be 50MB becomes 200MB because it pulled in postfix and other "recommended" packages.</li>
    <li><strong>Leaving the apt cache in Docker images:</strong> Forgetting <code>apt-get clean && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*</code> in Dockerfiles adds hundreds of MB to image size and leaves stale index files.</li>
    <li><strong>Not verifying GPG keys before adding repos:</strong> Adding a repo with an unverified key means trusting that server to deliver any package as root. Always verify the fingerprint matches the software vendor's published key.</li>
    <li><strong>Using <code>apt full-upgrade</code> (<code>dist-upgrade</code>) without understanding it:</strong> Unlike <code>apt upgrade</code>, <code>full-upgrade</code> can remove packages to resolve dependencies. Removing the wrong package on a production server causes outages.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- S10 -->
<div class="section" id="s10">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🛠</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Debugging Workflow</div><div class="section-num">Section 10 — Recovering from broken package states</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note note-debug">
    <div class="note-label">🛠 Package Troubleshooting Checklist</div>
    <p>Work through these steps in order. Most package problems are solved by steps 1–4.</p>
  </div>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Problem: "dpkg was interrupted, you must manually run 'dpkg --configure -a'"</span>
<span class="cn">dpkg --configure -a</span>               <span class="cm"># finish any interrupted installs</span>
<span class="cm"># If that fails:</span>
<span class="cn">apt install</span> <span class="fl">-f</span>                    <span class="cm"># fix broken dependencies</span>

<span class="cm"># Problem: "E: Could not get lock /var/lib/dpkg/lock"</span>
<span class="cm"># Another process is using apt/dpkg. Find it:</span>
<span class="cn">lsof /var/lib/dpkg/lock</span>
<span class="cm"># If it's a legitimate running process (apt, unattended-upgrades), wait</span>
<span class="cm"># If it's a zombie/stale lock:</span>
<span class="cn">ps aux</span> | <span class="cn">grep</span> <span class="st">"apt\|dpkg"</span>
<span class="cm"># Only remove lock files if NO apt/dpkg process is actually running:</span>
<span class="cm"># rm /var/lib/dpkg/lock /var/lib/dpkg/lock-frontend</span>
<span class="cm"># dpkg --configure -a</span>

<span class="cm"># Problem: "Unmet dependencies" / "broken packages"</span>
<span class="cn">apt install</span> <span class="fl">-f</span>                    <span class="cm"># attempt automatic fix</span>
<span class="cn">apt-cache policy</span> <span class="st">packagename</span>     <span class="cm"># check what version is available vs installed</span>
<span class="cn">apt-cache depends</span> <span class="st">packagename</span>    <span class="cm"># see what it needs</span>
<span class="cn">dpkg</span> <span class="fl">-l</span> | <span class="cn">grep</span> <span class="st">"^..r\|^..H"</span>     <span class="cm"># find packages in error states</span>

<span class="cm"># Problem: "Package not found" after you know it exists</span>
<span class="cn">apt update</span>                        <span class="cm"># refresh the package index</span>
<span class="cn">apt-cache search</span> <span class="st">partial-name</span>   <span class="cm"># maybe the package name is different</span>
<span class="cn">apt-cache policy</span> <span class="st">packagename</span>    <span class="cm"># is it available from any configured repo?</span>

<span class="cm"># Problem: apt update fails with "NO_PUBKEY ..."</span>
<span class="cm"># A repo's GPG key is missing or expired</span>
<span class="cn">apt-key adv --keyserver keyserver.ubuntu.com --recv-keys</span> <span class="st">KEYID</span>
<span class="cm"># Or re-download and install the repo's keyring package</span>

<span class="cm"># Problem: disk full during install</span>
<span class="cn">apt clean</span>                         <span class="cm"># free /var/cache/apt/archives first</span>
<span class="cn">apt autoremove</span>                    <span class="cm"># free orphaned packages</span>
<span class="cn">df -h</span>                             <span class="cm"># verify space freed</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S11 -->
<div class="section" id="s11">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔐</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Security Considerations</div><div class="section-num">Section 11</div></div>
  </div>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Package installs run as root with arbitrary scripts:</strong> Post-install scripts from a package can execute anything. This is why only trusted repositories should be added. Every <code>apt install</code> is a root-level trust decision.</li>
    <li><strong>Verify GPG key fingerprints out-of-band:</strong> Before adding a third-party repo, look up the GPG key fingerprint on the vendor's official website (not the README on GitHub). Verify it matches what you downloaded.</li>
    <li><strong>Disable automatic upgrades for critical services:</strong> Unattended-upgrades is good for security patches but can break things. Configure it to notify rather than auto-apply for packages like <code>postgresql</code>, <code>nginx</code>, <code>nodejs</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Minimal installs reduce attack surface:</strong> Every installed package is a potential vulnerability. Use <code>--no-install-recommends</code>. In containers, start from <code>ubuntu:22.04-minimal</code> or Alpine. Don't install build tools on production.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit installed packages regularly:</strong> <code>apt list --installed | wc -l</code>. Know what's on your servers. Unexpected packages are a compromise indicator.</li>
  </ul>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Check if any installed packages have known vulnerabilities:</span>
<span class="cn">apt install</span> debsecan              <span class="cm"># Debian security analysis</span>
<span class="cn">debsecan</span> <span class="fl">--suite</span> <span class="st">jammy</span>           <span class="cm"># report CVEs for installed packages</span>

<span class="cm"># Verify package file integrity (detect tampering after install):</span>
<span class="cn">debsums</span> <span class="st">nginx</span>                     <span class="cm"># check installed files against package checksums</span>
<span class="cn">debsums</span> <span class="fl">-s</span>                        <span class="cm"># -s: silent, only show changed files</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S12 -->
<div class="section" id="s12">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🚀</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Performance Considerations</div><div class="section-num">Section 12</div></div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>apt update is slow on many repos:</strong> Each source.list entry triggers a separate HTTP request to download a compressed index. Minimise the number of repos. Use <code>apt-cacher-ng</code> or Nexus as a local apt proxy for teams or CI systems that install the same packages repeatedly.</li>
    <li><strong><code>--no-install-recommends</code> drastically reduces install size:</strong> For servers and containers, this can save hundreds of MB. nginx recommends <code>fcgiwrap</code>, <code>nginx-doc</code>, and others you don't need on a bare web server.</li>
    <li><strong>Snap startup latency:</strong> Snaps have higher startup latency than deb-installed binaries due to squashfs mount overhead. Don't use snaps for hot-path CLI tools in CI pipelines. The Firefox snap on Ubuntu 22.04 starts noticeably slower than the deb version.</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-downloading packages:</strong> In CI pipelines that run apt install frequently, pre-download and cache <code>.deb</code> files in <code>/var/cache/apt/archives/</code> in your base Docker image to avoid repeated network fetches.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<!-- S13 -->
<div class="section" id="s13">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">💡</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Best Practices — Senior Level</div><div class="section-num">Section 13</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="senior-block">
    <h4>How a senior engineer thinks about package management</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>They never run <code>apt upgrade</code> on a production server without a plan: test on staging first, schedule a maintenance window, know which services need restart after.</li>
      <li>They pin critical packages — especially databases, web servers, and language runtimes — to known-good versions. Upgrades are deliberate decisions, not accidents triggered by <code>apt upgrade</code>.</li>
      <li>They treat every <code>apt install</code> as a security decision. They ask: do I trust this repo? Is this package from the official distro or a third party? What scripts does it run post-install?</li>
      <li>They maintain a list of explicitly installed packages and use it in provisioning automation. A server's package state is reproducible, not hand-crafted and forgotten.</li>
      <li>They use <code>apt-get</code> (not <code>apt</code>) in scripts. The stable, predictable output of <code>apt-get</code> is essential for reliable automation.</li>
      <li>They keep Docker image layers efficient: one <code>RUN</code> layer per logical step, always clean up the apt cache in the same layer.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <pre><code><span class="cm"># Reproducible package list pattern (for Ansible/provisioning):</span>
<span class="cm"># Generate list of manually-installed packages:</span>
<span class="cn">apt-mark showmanual</span> | <span class="cn">sort</span> > packages.txt

<span class="cm"># Restore on new system:</span>
<span class="cn">apt-get update</span> && <span class="cn">xargs apt-get install</span> <span class="fl">-y</span> < packages.txt

<span class="cm"># Safe upgrade workflow for production:</span>
<span class="cn">apt update</span>
<span class="cn">apt list</span> <span class="fl">--upgradable</span>              <span class="cm"># review what will change</span>
<span class="cn">apt upgrade</span> <span class="fl">--dry-run</span>            <span class="cm"># simulate with full output</span>
<span class="cm"># Review dry-run output carefully before proceeding</span>
<span class="cn">apt upgrade</span>                       <span class="cm"># execute in maintenance window</span></code></pre>
</div>

<!-- S14 -->
<div class="section" id="s14">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">🔥</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Real Incident Scenarios</div><div class="section-num">Section 14</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="incident">
    <div class="incident-label">🚨 Production Incident — Simulation</div>
    <h4>The Unplanned Kernel Upgrade</h4>
    <p><strong>Scenario:</strong> An engineer runs <code>apt upgrade</code> on a production database server during business hours to "just install a security patch." apt upgrades the kernel. The engineer doesn't reboot (new kernel needs reboot). Two weeks later an automated script reboots the server for a different reason. The server comes up on the new kernel — which is incompatible with the custom DKMS module for the RAID controller. Server doesn't fully boot. Database offline for 4 hours.</p>
    <p><strong>Prevention:</strong></p>
    <pre style="margin:8px 0"><code><span class="cm"># Always hold kernel packages on production servers</span>
<span class="cn">apt-mark hold</span> linux-image-$(uname -r) linux-headers-$(uname -r)
<span class="cn">apt-mark hold</span> linux-image-generic linux-headers-generic
<span class="cm"># Schedule kernel upgrades explicitly with full boot testing</span></code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="incident">
    <div class="incident-label">🚨 Production Incident — Simulation</div>
    <h4>dpkg Lock During Deployment</h4>
    <p><strong>Scenario:</strong> A deployment script runs <code>apt install myapp</code> on multiple servers simultaneously. On two servers the <code>unattended-upgrades</code> process was already running (triggered by a cron job). The deployment fails with "Could not get lock /var/lib/dpkg/lock". The deploy script panics, removes the lock file, and runs dpkg — corrupting the package state mid-install. Three packages end up half-installed.</p>
    <p><strong>Recovery:</strong></p>
    <pre style="margin:8px 0"><code><span class="cn">dpkg --configure -a</span>               <span class="cm"># finish half-configured packages</span>
<span class="cn">apt install</span> <span class="fl">-f</span>                    <span class="cm"># fix broken deps</span>
<span class="cn">apt-get install</span> <span class="fl">--reinstall</span> <span class="st">pkg1 pkg2 pkg3</span>  <span class="cm"># reinstall corrupted ones</span></code></pre>
    <p><strong>Prevention:</strong> Use <code>systemctl stop unattended-upgrades</code> before deployment scripts, or use <code>flock</code> to wait for the dpkg lock rather than removing it.</p>
  </div>
</div>

