<!-- S16 -->
<div class="section" id="s16">
  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="section-icon">💣</div>
    <div><div class="section-title">Break It & Fix It</div><div class="section-num">Section 16</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="note note-break">
    <div class="note-label">🧪 Break It & Fix It — All recoverable on a test VM</div>
  </div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Break 1 — Stale index:</strong> Delete the apt lists directory: <code>sudo rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*</code>. Try <code>apt install tree</code>. Observe the "unable to locate package" error. Fix: <code>sudo apt update</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Break 2 — Simulate half-installed:</strong> Start installing a package and kill it mid-way with Ctrl+C. Run <code>dpkg -l | grep "^.H"</code> to see the half-installed state. Recover with <code>sudo dpkg --configure -a</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Break 3 — Bad sources entry:</strong> Add a deliberately wrong line to <code>/etc/apt/sources.list.d/bad.list</code>: <code>deb http://not-a-real-repo.example.com/ubuntu jammy main</code>. Run <code>apt update</code>. Observe the error. Fix: remove or correct the file.</li>
    <li><strong>Break 4 — Double-add a repo:</strong> Add the same repo twice in two different files in <code>sources.list.d/</code>. Run <code>apt update</code>. Observe the "duplicate source" warning. Fix by removing one.</li>
    <li><strong>Break 5 — The apt cache fill:</strong> Run <code>sudo apt-get download $(apt list --installed 2>/dev/null | awk -F/ 'NR>1{print $1}' | head -20)</code> to fill the cache. Check <code>du -sh /var/cache/apt/archives/</code>. Clean: <code>sudo apt clean</code>.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

